              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> is called <html:em><html:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></html:strong></html:em> when all of its <fr:link href="/foreign/erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001Q/" title="Fiber" uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001Q/" display-uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001Q" type="local">fibers</fr:link> are <fr:link href="/foreign/erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001G/" title="n-truncated type" uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001G/" display-uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001G" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span> types</fr:link>. By analogy, we shall also refer to maps as <html:em><html:strong>contractible</html:strong></html:em> when their fibers are; we shall refer to maps as <html:em><html:strong>propositional</html:strong></html:em> when their fibers are <fr:link href="/foreign/erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001I/" title="Proposition" uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001I/" display-uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-001I" type="local">propositions</fr:link>.</html:p>
